# Part 4 – Exploratory PCA

## Missing Value Imputation

Prior to PCA, missing values are replaced by half of the smallest positive value observed for each feature.

```r
missing_value = min_positive / 2
```

---

## Log Transformation

```r
log10(x + 1)
```

is applied to stabilize variance.

---

## Principal Component Analysis

```r
pca <- prcomp(
  t(mat_log),
  scale. = TRUE
)
```

Variance explained is calculated for each principal component.

---

## PCA Visualizations

The following plots should be generated:

### Initial PCA

```text
All samples
```

### PCA Colored by Biological Groups, QCs, and Blanks

In addition to PCA visualizations based on sample type, it is recommended to generate a PCA simultaneously highlighting biological groups, quality control samples (QCs), and analytical blanks.

This visualization allows assessment of:

- QC clustering;
- separation between blanks and biological samples;
- preliminary biological trends among experimental groups;
- potential outliers or unexpected sample behavior.

```r
pca_neg_df <- pca_neg_df %>%
  mutate(
    plot_group = case_when(
      sample_type == "blank" ~ "Blank",
      sample_type == "qc" ~ "QC",
      TRUE ~ group
    )
  )

ggplot(
  pca_neg_df,
  aes(
    PC1,
    PC2,
    color = plot_group
  )
) +
  geom_point(size = 3) +
  theme_bw()

### PCA Without Blanks

```text
Biological samples + QCs
```

### QC Clustering PCA

```text
QCs versus biological samples
```

